data.content:
Yes — the direct cast will throw an `InvalidCastException` on failure instead of a clear test failure message. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` to verify the type, then cast:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler));
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This gives a descriptive test failure ("Expected type EmailHandler, actual type X") rather than an unhandled exception. If you're on **.NET 8+ / MSTest 3.x**, you can use the generic version for even cleaner code:

```csharp
Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
```
